erg, Saxony, Germany","Chemnitz, Saxony, Germany":"Chemnitz, Saxony, Germany","Pockau, Marienberg, Chemnitz, Sachsen, Germany":"Pockau, Kreis Marienberg, Saxony, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Reichel","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Otto, Arno, Fritz, Gerhardt, Heinz, Helmut, Herwig, Rudi, Ulrich, Wolfgang.","German: from a pet form of any of several ancient Germanic personal names formed with the ancient Germanic element <i>rīc</i> ‘power’.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from the Yiddish female personal name <i>Raykhl</i>, a pet form of <i>Raykhe</i>, which in turn is derived from Yiddish <i>raykh</i> ‘rich’."],"variants":[{"name":"Reichelt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Erna, Gerhard, Klaus, Lothar, Reiner, Wilhelm.","variant of   Reichel   1.","variant of   Reichel   1 + excrescent <i>-t</i>."]},{"name":"Reichle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Albrecht, Claus, Fritz, Hans, Otto, Wieland.","South German:","variant of   Reichel   1."]},{"name":"Reichl","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Gunter, Hans.","German (Bavaria): variant of   Reichel   1."]},{"name":"Rajchel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Jozef, Janusz, Ryszard.","Polish: from German   Reichel  ."]}]},{"name":"Jorg","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Dialectal (Alemannic and Swabian) form of   Georg ."],"variants":[{"name":"George","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Jorg Reichel was born in 1502, in Pockau, Kreis Marienberg, Saxony, Germany as the son of Nickel Reichel. He married Elisabetha about 1529, in Chemnitz, Saxony, Germany. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1502–":"1502–Surnud","1502–Male":"1502–Surnud","1505–Male":"1505–Surnud","1507–Male":"1507–Surnud","1509–Male":"1509–Surnud","1512–Female":"1512–Surnud","1506–Female":"1506–Surnud","1534–Male":"1534–Surnud","1476–1540":"1476–1540","about 1529":"umbes 1529","1502":"1502","1534":"1534","1512":"1512","1476":"1476","about 1534":"umbes 1534","1540":"1540","1509":"1509","1507":"1507","1506":"1506","1505":"1505","Stolzenhain, Wünschendorf, Lengefeld, Marienberg, Chemnitz, Sachsen, Germany":"Stolzenhain, Wünschendorf, Kreis Marienberg, Sachsen, Saksamaa","Chemnitz, Saxony, Germany":"Chemnitz, Sachsen, Saksamaa","Pockau, Marienberg, Chemnitz, Sachsen, Germany":"Pockau, Kreis Marienberg, Sachsen, Saksamaa"},"fi":{"1502–":"1502–Kuollut","1502–Male":"1502–Kuollut","1505–Male":"1505–Kuollut","1507–Male":"1507–Kuollut","1509–Male":"1509–Kuollut","1512–Female":"1512–Kuollut","1506–Female":"1506–Kuollut","1534–Male":"1534–Kuollut","1476–1540":"1476–1540","about 1529":"noin 1529","1502":"1502","1534":"1534","1512":"1512","1476":"1476","about 1534":"noin 